For Next-Ranker, you now need a schema that supports:

3 roles → ADMIN, EXAM_HANDLER, USER

ExamHandler manages multiple exams

Tests → free or paid

TestSeries → collection of tests

Subscription plans → unlock paid tests

Live tests → scheduled + random questions

Admin creates subscription plans

Below is a clean scalable Prisma schema that supports all of that.

🧠 Core Roles System
Use role enum.

enum Role {
  ADMIN
  EXAM_HANDLER
  USER
}
👤 User Model
model User {
  id        String   @id @default(cuid())
  name      String?
  email     String   @unique
  password  String
  role      Role     @default(USER)
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  examsHandled ExamHandlerExam[]
  attempts     Attempt[]
  subscriptions UserSubscription[]
}
📚 Category → Exam Structure
model Category {
  id    String @id @default(cuid())
  name  String
  slug  String @unique

  exams Exam[]
}

model Exam {
  id          String @id @default(cuid())
  name        String
  slug        String @unique
  categoryId  String
  createdAt   DateTime @default(now())

  category Category @relation(fields: [categoryId], references: [id])

  handlers   ExamHandlerExam[]
  tests      Test[]
  testSeries TestSeries[]
  liveTests  LiveTest[]
}
👨‍🏫 Exam Handler Mapping
One handler can manage multiple exams.

model ExamHandlerExam {
  id        String @id @default(cuid())
  handlerId String
  examId    String

  handler User @relation(fields: [handlerId], references: [id])
  exam    Exam @relation(fields: [examId], references: [id])

  @@unique([handlerId, examId])
}
📝 Tests
Tests can be free or paid.

enum TestStatus {
  DRAFT
  PUBLISHED
}

model Test {
  id           String @id @default(cuid())
  title        String
  examId       String
  duration     Int
  totalMarks   Int
  isPaid       Boolean @default(false)
  status       TestStatus @default(DRAFT)
  createdAt    DateTime @default(now())

  exam       Exam @relation(fields: [examId], references: [id])
  questions  Question[]
  testSeries TestSeriesTest[]
  attempts   Attempt[]
}
🧩 Questions
model Question {
  id       String @id @default(cuid())
  question String

  optionA  String
  optionB  String
  optionC  String
  optionD  String

  correct  String
  marks    Int

  testId String
  test   Test @relation(fields: [testId], references: [id])
}
📦 Test Series
A TestSeries = collection of tests.

model TestSeries {
  id      String @id @default(cuid())
  title   String
  examId  String
  isPaid  Boolean @default(false)
  price   Float?

  exam  Exam @relation(fields: [examId], references: [id])
  tests TestSeriesTest[]
}

model TestSeriesTest {
  id          String @id @default(cuid())
  testSeriesId String
  testId       String

  testSeries TestSeries @relation(fields: [testSeriesId], references: [id])
  test       Test       @relation(fields: [testId], references: [id])

  @@unique([testSeriesId, testId])
}
💳 Subscription Plans (Admin Creates)
model SubscriptionPlan {
  id          String @id @default(cuid())
  name        String
  price       Float
  duration    Int  // days
  description String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  users UserSubscription[]
}
👥 User Subscription
model UserSubscription {
  id        String @id @default(cuid())
  userId    String
  planId    String
  startDate DateTime
  endDate   DateTime

  user User @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id])
  plan SubscriptionPlan @relation(fields: [planId], references: [id])
}
This means:

If a user buys subscription → access all paid tests.

🔴 Live Tests
Live tests scheduled by ExamHandler.

model LiveTest {
  id           String @id @default(cuid())
  examId       String
  title        String
  startTime    DateTime
  duration     Int
  questionCount Int
  isPaid       Boolean @default(false)

  exam Exam @relation(fields: [examId], references: [id])

  attempts LiveAttempt[]
}
📊 Attempts
model Attempt {
  id      String @id @default(cuid())
  userId  String
  testId  String
  score   Int
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  user User @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id])
  test Test @relation(fields: [testId], references: [id])
}

model LiveAttempt {
  id         String @id @default(cuid())
  userId     String
  liveTestId String
  score      Int

  user     User     @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id])
  liveTest LiveTest @relation(fields: [liveTestId], references: [id])
}
