Below are additional Prisma models you can plug into your existing schema to support the features you mentioned. I’ll keep them modular so they integrate cleanly with the schema you already designed.

🚀 Additional Models for Advanced Features
1️⃣ Exam Syllabus
Each exam can have multiple syllabus sections (subject → topic → description).

model ExamSyllabus {
  id          String @id @default(cuid())
  examId      String
  subject     String
  topic       String
  description String?

  exam Exam @relation(fields: [examId], references: [id])
}
Example:

Exam	Subject	Topic
JEE Main	Physics	Mechanics
JEE Main	Chemistry	Organic Chemistry
2️⃣ Topics (for Topic-wise Questions)
This allows filtering questions by topic and building topic-wise tests.

model Topic {
  id        String @id @default(cuid())
  examId    String
  name      String
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  exam Exam @relation(fields: [examId], references: [id])

  questions QuestionTopic[]
}
3️⃣ Question ↔ Topic Mapping
One question can belong to multiple topics.

model QuestionTopic {
  id         String @id @default(cuid())
  questionId String
  topicId    String

  question Question @relation(fields: [questionId], references: [id])
  topic    Topic    @relation(fields: [topicId], references: [id])

  @@unique([questionId, topicId])
}
Example:

Question → Physics → Mechanics
Question → Physics → Rotational Motion
4️⃣ AI Difficulty Tagging
Allows AI to classify questions.

enum Difficulty {
  EASY
  MEDIUM
  HARD
}
Add this field inside Question model:

difficulty Difficulty @default(MEDIUM)
aiScore    Float?
Example:

Question	Difficulty	AI Score
Q1	EASY	0.22
Q2	HARD	0.89
5️⃣ Negative Marking
Each test can define its marking scheme.

Add this to Test model.

negativeMarks Float @default(0)
Example:

Test	Marks	Negative
JEE Mock	4	1
Meaning:

correct = +4
wrong = -1
6️⃣ Leaderboard
Stores ranking for each test.

model Leaderboard {
  id        String @id @default(cuid())
  testId    String
  userId    String
  score     Int
  timeTaken Int
  rank      Int

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  test Test @relation(fields: [testId], references: [id])
  user User @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id])

  @@unique([testId, userId])
